## Chapter 3 ‚Äî Methods Common to All Objects

**Item 10 ‚Äî Obey the general contract when overriding equals**
Override `equals` only for value classes needing logical equality. Obey reflexivity, symmetry, transitivity, consistency, and non-nullity. Prefer composition over inheritance when adding value components. **Records:** generated `equals` satisfies the contract ‚Äî do not hand-roll unless necessary.

**Item 11 ‚Äî Always override hashCode when you override equals**
Every class overriding `equals` must override `hashCode` consistently. **Records:** generated `hashCode` satisfies this automatically.

**Item 12 ‚Äî Always override toString**
Provide a useful `toString` for value classes to aid debugging. **Records:** default is usually sufficient; customize when domain names matter. Skip for static utility classes and enums.

**Item 13 ‚Äî Override clone judiciously**
Avoid `Cloneable` and `clone()`. Prefer copy constructors or static factory copy methods.

**Item 14 ‚Äî Consider implementing Comparable**
Implement `Comparable` when a natural ordering exists. Use `Integer.compare`, `Comparator.comparing`, etc. ‚Äî not relational operators on boxed types.

---

## Chapter 4 ‚Äî Classes and Interfaces

**Item 15 ‚Äî Minimize the accessibility of classes and members**
Make each class and member as inaccessible as possible. Package-private by default in Maestro; public only for layer API. Never expose mutable objects via `public static final`. Test-only relaxation: at most package-private, not public.

**Item 16 ‚Äî In public classes, use accessor methods, not public fields**
No public fields in public API types. **Records** expose components via accessors ‚Äî acceptable for immutable data carriers.

**Item 17 ‚Äî Minimize mutability**
Prefer immutable types. **Records** are the default for domain/API (`parser.model`). Mutable state only in infrastructure adapters. Defensive-copy mutable components on input; never expose mutable internals.

**Item 18 ‚Äî Favor composition over inheritance**
Prefer composition and forwarding over subclassing concrete classes. Maestro: sealed `Expression` / `ProcessingStage` hierarchies instead of deep inheritance trees.

**Item 19 ‚Äî Design and document for inheritance or else prohibit it**
Do not subclass unless designed for it. **Sealed** types and `final` classes prohibit unsafe extension. Never call overridable methods from constructors.

**Item 20 ‚Äî Prefer interfaces to abstract classes**
Define capabilities with interfaces. Maestro: program to `Expression`, `ProcessingStage`, `Literal`.

**Item 21 ‚Äî Design interfaces for posterity**
Interfaces are permanent contracts ‚Äî design for evolution (default methods sparingly; document behavior).

**Item 22 ‚Äî Use interfaces only to define types**
Do not use interfaces purely as constant holders or utility namespaces ‚Äî use classes (Item 4).

**Item 23 ‚Äî Prefer class hierarchies to tagged classes**
Replace type-tag fields with sealed class/interface hierarchies. Maestro: `ProcessingStage` permits known stage records.

**Item 24 ‚Äî Favor static member classes over nonstatic**
Use static nested classes unless the nested class needs enclosing instance access. Avoid nonstatic inner classes in public API.

**Item 25 ‚Äî Limit source files to a single top-level class**
One public top-level type per file; filename matches the type name.

---

## Chapter 5 ‚Äî Generics

**Item 26 ‚Äî Don't use raw types**
Never use raw generic types. Always parameterize `List`, `Map`, `Optional`, etc.

**Item 27 ‚Äî Eliminate unchecked warnings**
Fix or `@SuppressWarnings("unchecked")` only with minimal scope and comment justifying safety (e.g. varargs bridges).

**Item 28 ‚Äî Prefer lists to arrays**
Prefer `List<E>` over arrays for public APIs. Use `List.of`, `toList()` for immutable lists.

**Item 29 ‚Äî Favor generic types**
Define generic types when type parameters improve safety and clarity (`Stack<T>`, not `Stack` of `Object`).

**Item 30 ‚Äî Favor generic methods**
Use generic methods and type inference (`<T> T requireNonNull(T obj)`) over raw casts.

**Item 31 ‚Äî Use bounded wildcards to increase API flexibility**
Use `? extends T` for producers, `? super T` for consumers (PECS). Apply to public API parameters and return types.

**Item 32 ‚Äî Combine generics and varargs judiciously**
Varargs on generic types can be unsafe; prefer `List<T>` arguments. If varargs are required, document and suppress carefully.

**Item 33 ‚Äî Consider typesafe heterogeneous containers**
Use `Class<?>` keys (e.g. `Map<Class<?>, Object>`) when one container must hold multiple types safely ‚Äî rare; prefer typed fields.

---

## Chapter 6 ‚Äî Enums and Annotations

**Item 34 ‚Äî Use enums instead of int constants**
Use enums for fixed sets of constants. Maestro: `ComparisonOperator`, `WindowType`, `LogicalOperator` ‚Äî no magic strings or int codes.

**Item 35 ‚Äî Use instance fields instead of ordinals**
Never use `ordinal()` for business logic. Store associated data as enum instance fields.

**Item 36 ‚Äî Use EnumSet instead of bit fields**
Use `EnumSet` for sets of enum constants ‚Äî not manual bit masks.

**Item 37 ‚Äî Use EnumMap instead of ordinal indexing**
Use `EnumMap` for enum-keyed maps ‚Äî not arrays indexed by `ordinal()`.

**Item 38 ‚Äî Emulate extensible enums with interfaces**
When enum constants need polymorphic behavior, implement interfaces on enum constants (rare).

**Item 39 ‚Äî Prefer annotations to naming patterns**
Use `@Override`, `@Deprecated`, `@SafeVarargs`, etc. ‚Äî not naming conventions alone.

**Item 40 ‚Äî Consistently use the Override annotation**
Mark every intended method override with `@Override` ‚Äî catches typos at compile time.

**Item 41 ‚Äî Use marker interfaces to define types**
Use marker interfaces (e.g. `Serializable`) sparingly; prefer annotations or explicit API contracts.

---

## Chapter 7 ‚Äî Lambdas and Streams

**Item 42 ‚Äî Prefer lambdas to anonymous classes**
Use lambdas for functional interfaces unless you need multiple methods or stateful anonymous classes.

**Item 43 ‚Äî Prefer method references to lambdas**
Use method references (`records::add`, `Type::method`) when they are clearer than lambdas.

**Item 44 ‚Äî Favor the use of standard functional interfaces**
Use `Predicate`, `Function`, `Consumer`, `Supplier` from `java.util.function` ‚Äî do not define one-off functional interfaces when standard ones fit.

**Item 45 ‚Äî Use streams judiciously**
Streams for transforms and aggregations; prefer simple loops when clearer or when performance matters on small collections.

**Item 46 ‚Äî Prefer side-effect-free functions in streams**
Keep stream pipelines pure; perform I/O and mutation outside the pipeline (in `.run()` actions in tests).

**Item 47 ‚Äî Prefer Collection to Stream as a return type**
Return `Collection`, `List`, or `Set` ‚Äî not `Stream` ‚Äî from public methods. Streams are for internal computation.

**Item 48 ‚Äî Use caution when making streams parallel**
Do not use parallel streams by default. Parallelize only when measured benefit exists and operations are side-effect-free.

---

## Chapter 8 ‚Äî Methods

**Item 49 ‚Äî Check parameters for validity**
Validate constructor and method parameters early. Use `Objects.requireNonNull`; throw `NullPointerException` or `IllegalArgumentException` with detail. Validate in parser/builder layers ‚Äî not inside records.

**Item 50 ‚Äî Make defensive copies when needed**
Defensive-copy mutable inputs in constructors and accessors. Use `List.copyOf`, `Stream.toList()` in records.

**Item 51 ‚Äî Design method signatures carefully**
Keep methods focused; avoid long parameter lists (use builder or value object). Use overloading only when truly clearer.

**Item 52 ‚Äî Use overloading judiciously**
Do not overload methods where calls could be ambiguous. Record convenience constructors (e.g. `Query(..., String... sinkTopics)`) are OK when unambiguous.

**Item 53 ‚Äî Use varargs judiciously**
Use varargs for trailing arguments of the same type (`String... sinkTopics`). Never use varargs with generic types unsafely (Item 32).

**Item 54 ‚Äî Return empty collections or arrays, not nulls**
Return `List.of()`, `Set.of()`, `Optional.empty()` ‚Äî never `null` collections or arrays from public methods.

**Item 55 ‚Äî Return optionals judiciously**
Use `Optional` for optional return values (`SourceStage.whereClause`). Do not use Optional for fields, parameters, collections, or as a general null substitute.

**Item 56 ‚Äî Write doc comments for all exposed API elements**
Document every public/protected member of exported API types (SDK, operator, `StreamTopologyParser`) with `{@code}`, `@param`, `@return`, `@throws`.

---

## Chapter 9 ‚Äî General Programming

**Item 57 ‚Äî Minimize the scope of local variables**
Declare variables in the smallest scope; use `var` when the type is obvious from the initializer.

**Item 58 ‚Äî Prefer for-each loops to traditional for loops**
Use enhanced for over index loops when iteration order follows the collection.

**Item 59 ‚Äî Know and use the libraries**
Prefer JDK utilities (`Objects`, `List.of`, `Map.of`, `EnumSet`, AssertJ in tests) over reinventing. Know Kafka/Jackson/ANTLR APIs before wrapping them.

**Item 60 ‚Äî Avoid float and double if exact answers are required**
Use `BigDecimal` for exact decimal arithmetic ‚Äî not `float` or `double` for money or precise values.

**Item 61 ‚Äî Prefer primitive types to boxed primitives**
Use primitives locally when null is not needed; boxed types for generics and collections only.

**Item 62 ‚Äî Avoid strings where other types are more appropriate**
Model domain concepts as types (records, enums) ‚Äî not strings. Maestro: stages and expressions are records, not `String` blobs.

**Item 63 ‚Äî Beware the performance of string concatenation**
Do not concatenate strings repeatedly in loops; use `StringBuilder`. In logging, use SLF4J `{}` placeholders ‚Äî not concatenation.

**Item 64 ‚Äî Refer to objects by their interfaces**
Declare fields, parameters, and return types as interface types (`List`, `Map`, `Expression`) ‚Äî not concrete implementations.

**Item 65 ‚Äî Prefer interfaces to reflection**
Avoid reflection in normal code paths. Use interfaces, generics, and method references.

**Item 66 ‚Äî Use native methods judiciously**
Avoid JNI unless strictly required ‚Äî not applicable to typical Maestro code.

**Item 67 ‚Äî Optimize judiciously**
Measure before optimizing. Prefer clear code over premature micro-optimization.

**Item 68 ‚Äî Adhere to generally accepted naming conventions**
Types: `UpperCamelCase`. Methods/fields: `lowerCamelCase`. Constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`. Packages: lowercase (`dev.vepo.maestro.parser.model`). Test methods: `shouldBehavior`.

